      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i was also wondering about the safety side of things. if i'm planning on stashing a pretty large amount in one of these, is it better to just keep it all in one place to maximize the interest, or is there a risk to having it all tucked away in a single account?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Having a large amount of money in one account can be a bit of a risk, especially if you're storing it in a single institution. You're essentially putting all your eggs in one basket, which can be a problem if the institution experiences financial difficulties or is compromised by a security breach.\n\nIt's a bit like having a single, very valuable item in a home safe - if the safe is stolen or compromised, you could lose everything. To mitigate this risk, you might consider diversifying your emergency fund across multiple institutions, similar to how a traditional investment portfolio is diversified.\n\nFor example, you could consider splitting your emergency fund across three or four accounts, each with a different institution. This way, if one account is compromised or experiences financial difficulties, you'll still have access to your money in the other accounts.\n\nIt's also worth considering the FDIC insurance coverage, which typically applies to accounts up to $250,000 per depositor, per insured bank. This means that if an institution experiences financial difficulties, you may be able to recover your money by transferring it to another FDIC-insured institution.\n\nIn the case of the institutions I mentioned earlier, Ally, Marcus by Goldman Sachs, and SoFi, all three are FDIC-insured",
